description:
Hi,
the [language compatibility|https://www.mongodb.com/docs/drivers/java/sync/current/compatibility/#language-compatibility] section states that 4.6 version is compatible with java 11 but when using it in a project with a version < 17 you get

 
{noformat}
java.lang.UnsupportedClassVersionError: org/bson/codecs/record/RecordCodecProvider has been compiled by a more recent version of the Java Runtime (class file version 61.0), this version of the Java Runtime only recognizes class file versions up to…){noformat}
This happens becase  {{ mongodb-driver-core}} pulls {{{}bson-record-codec{}}}, and record-codec naturally requires a java 17.

 

 
{noformat}
[INFO] |  +- org.mongodb:mongodb-driver-core:jar:4.6.0:compile
[INFO] |  |  \- org.mongodb:bson-record-codec:jar:4.6.0:runtime{noformat}
 If {{bson-record-codec}} is excluded manually one get into a

 

 
{noformat}
java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: org/bson/codecs/record/RecordCodecProvider` because the class is loaded while accessing MongoClientSettings.{noformat}
 

because the codec provided ({{{}Jep395RecordCodecProvider{}}}) is instanced without reflection at [MongoClientSettings|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-java-driver/blob/ba1cf0ba2fbabcf3b4eb46643860e863a83fe822/driver-core/src/main/com/mongodb/MongoClientSettings.java#L77]
{noformat}
@Immutable
public final class MongoClientSettings {
    private static final CodecRegistry DEFAULT_CODEC_REGISTRY =
            fromProviders(asList(new ValueCodecProvider(),
                    new BsonValueCodecProvider(),
                    new DBRefCodecProvider(),
                    new DBObjectCodecProvider(),
                    new DocumentCodecProvider(new DocumentToDBRefTransformer()),
                    new IterableCodecProvider(new DocumentToDBRefTransformer()),
                    new MapCodecProvider(new DocumentToDBRefTransformer()),
                    new GeoJsonCodecProvider(),
                    new GridFSFileCodecProvider(),
                    new Jsr310CodecProvider(),
                    new JsonObjectCodecProvider(),
                    new BsonCodecProvider(),
                    new EnumCodecProvider(),
                    new Jep395RecordCodecProvider()));{noformat}
I'm reporting this issue because I:
 * couldn't find it already created
 * got confused with the documentation
 * for a breaking change I was expecting a major version bump.

 

Regards,

  Juan.

A JSON document like

{code:json}
{
   operationTime : {$timestamp : {t : 40, i : 20}
}
{code}

should parse even though the "t" and "i" fields are unquoted.  In 3.5 it throws an exception:

{noformat}
org.bson.json.JsonParseException: JSON reader expected a string but found 't'.

	at org.bson.json.JsonReader.readStringFromExtendedJson(JsonReader.java:1126)
	at org.bson.json.JsonReader.visitTimestampExtendedJson(JsonReader.java:1146)
	at org.bson.json.JsonReader.visitExtendedJSON(JsonReader.java:626)
	at org.bson.json.JsonReader.readBsonType(JsonReader.java:148
{noformat}

h4. Summary

In bson/src/test/unit/org/bson/codecs/pojo/entities/ConventionModel.java, the constructor ConventionModel(customId, child, simpleModel) is missing a parameter for myIntField, which is instead assigned to itself.
{code:java}
public ConventionModel(final String customId, final ConventionModel child, final SimpleModel simpleModel) {
    this.myIntField = myIntField;
    this.customId = customId;
    this.child = child;
    this.simpleModel = simpleModel;
} 
{code}
Version: latest

h4. Summary

Hello everyone,

When attempting to create a new collection when it already exists, an IllegalStateException is thrown, in addition to the usual MongoCommandException.

This is a bug since the sync driver only throws the MongoCommandException, and this problem appears with the reactive streams driver since version 4.7.0 only.

h4. How to Reproduce

 
{code:java}
MongoClient mongoClient = MongoClients.create();
MongoDatabase exampleDatabase = mongoClient.getDatabase("foo");

SubscriberHelpers.ObservableSubscriber<Void> voidSubscriber = new SubscriberHelpers.OperationSubscriber<>();
exampleDatabase.createCollection("bar").subscribe(voidSubscriber);
voidSubscriber.await(); 
{code}
 

If the collection already exists, you should see this stack trace: [https://gist.github.com/Romitou/f552416d07f9608e2ddbecfa5c03e309|https://gist.github.com/Romitou/f552416d07f9608e2ddbecfa5c03e309]
h4. Additional Background

As said before, this bug only appears from version 4.7.0 and only on the reactive streams driver, I think this is relevant information.
